<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1863-02-14T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1863-02-14T00:00:00-05:00" n="83" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d83">
                        <head><persName type="from">Mr. Seward</persName> to <persName type="to">Mr.
                                Adams</persName>.</head>
                        <opener>
                            <seg rendition="#left">No. 478.]</seg>
                            <dateline rendition="#right">
                                <placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Department of State</hi>, <hi rend="italic">Washington,</hi></placeName>
                                <date calendar="gregorian" when="1863-02-14"><hi rend="italic">February</hi> 14, 1863.</date></dateline></opener>
                        <p><hi rend="smallcaps">Sir:</hi> I have to acknowledge the receipt of your
                            despatch (No. 304) of the 23d ultimo, relative to your calling Earl
                            Russell’s attention to an instance during the Crimean war, in which it
                            seems that Great Britain demanded the restitution of a vessel in
                            circumstances similar, to those which belong to the case of the Emily
                            St. Pierre, and to inform you that your proceedings, as therein stated,
                            are approved.</p>
                        <p>I am, sir, your obedient servant,</p>
                        <closer>
                            <signed>WILLIAM H. SEWARD.</signed></closer>
                        <postscript>
                            <p><hi rend="smallcaps">Charles Francis Adams</hi>, Esq., <hi rend="italic">&amp;c., &amp;c., &amp;c.</hi></p>
                        </postscript>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>